1 Previously on R Workshops : topics covered in the last section

In R Workshop 3, we…:

  • … Learn how to explore your data: how to subset data parts, matching elements, merging and binding your data
  • … Data manipulations: how to use the paste() function, rename your elements, use the seq() function
  • … Basic visualisation: type of plots and how to make them, how to plot on top of plots, add to your plot, manipulate margins, composite plots and exporting your plots

If many of these learning outcomes sound unfamiliar, you may want to consider doing R Workshop 3 before today’s workshop.

2 Learning outcomes

Today you will learn about:

On completion of this session you should be able to:

  • Import a dataset in csv format into R, assign it to a dataframe and explore the data
  • Use descriptive statistics to describe numeric and categorical variables
  • Use the normal distribution defined by the mean and standard deviation to find specified statistics, and test a continuous variable for normality
  • Find confidence intervals for the mean of a continuous variable
  • Perform random sampling from a dataset or from a defined distribution
  • Visualise a dataset graphically using appropriate plots
  • Explore relationships between variables, including use of inferential analyses.

3 Set-up

To start, set your chosen working directory using the ‘setwd’ command, or alternatively using the menu: Session>Set Working Directory>Choose Directory.

4 Data

We will use a dataset called bp_dataset, provided as a csv file. The dataset is based on a clinical trial to test the effect of two drugs (Drug A and Drug B), compared with an inactive control drug (placebo), on blood pressure in people who have high blood pressure. The purpose of the drugs is to reduce blood pressure. Some additional information about the people in the trial, such as their age and sex, is also provided (see codebook for further information about the variables).

Let’s start by loading the dataset. You need to ensure that the dataset is located in your working directory (Section 3). Read in the csv file and assign it to a dataframe: we will call the dataframe bp_dataset. The ‘header’ argument allows us to set the column headings as variable names when set to TRUE.

bp_dataset<-read.csv(file="bp_dataset.csv", header=TRUE)

Take a look at the column heads.

head(bp_dataset)
##   ptid male age intervention bp_baseline bp_3m bp_6m
## 1    1    1  41       Drug B         218   153   163
## 2    2    0  46       Drug B         200   162   177
## 3    3    0  37       Drug A         198   122   166
## 4    4    0  46       Drug A         202   148   128
## 5    5    1  44      Control         142   196   231
## 6    6    1  36       Drug B         148   191   164

Let’s find out how many rows (observations) and variables (columns) are in this dataset.

nrow(bp_dataset)
## [1] 100
ncol(bp_dataset)
## [1] 7

You can also use the ‘dim’ command (for dimensions), outputting number of rows and number of columns.

dim(bp_dataset)
## [1] 100   7

We need to check the types of variable in the dataframe. Remember there are 5 main data types in R:

  • character
  • numeric
  • integer
  • logical
  • complex

In this session, we are only considering character, numeric, integer and logical. Character variables may also be known as text or string variables.

In this dataset we have both integer and character variables (see the code snippet below). The variable male is an integer coded as 0 and 1, but could also be a character variable i.e. recorded as “Male”, “Female”. The variable intervention is a character variable, but could be an integer coded, for example, as Control=0, Drug A=1, Drug B=2.

The ‘str’ command allows us to check the structure of the dataframe.

str(bp_dataset)

5 Topics

5.1 Basic statistics

From the dataset, there are 4 variables that include numeric data, that is, the information is an actual number rather than using numbers as codes. These are age, and blood pressure measured at three timepoints (bp_baseline, bp_3m, bp_6m).

We want to find the mean, median, standard deviation and variance for these variables. Let’s start with the mean. To find the mean for age we can use:

mean(bp_dataset$age)
## [1] 49.03

We can attach the dataframe bp_dataset, so we don’t need to use the $ notation for each command. Remember to use the ‘detach’ command when you wish to detach the dataframe.

attach(bp_dataset)

mean(age)
## [1] 49.03


5.1.0.1 Task 1

Find the means for bp_baseline and bp_3m.

mean(bp_baseline)
## [1] 182.4
mean(bp_3m)
## [1] 165.88


We can summarise for different subsets of the data by using R command ‘tapply’. The ‘tapply’ command takes 3 arguments in the below command:

  • age: numeric variable for which we wish to calculate the mean
  • male: variable indicating the subgroups, in this case 0 and 1
  • mean: the statistic we wish to calculate
tapply(age, male, mean)
##        0        1 
## 51.94595 47.31746

We can also use the code below. This calculates the mean for males [male==1]. Remember to use == to set the value of the variable male to be equal to 1.

mean(age[male==1])
## [1] 47.31746


We can do the same for intervention group.

tapply(age, intervention, mean)
##  Control   Drug A   Drug B 
## 51.42857 50.61765 45.84211

Let’s say we want to calculate the mean age by sex and intervention group. We can use the ‘aggregate’ command. The FUN argument means function, which is the mean in this example.

aggregate(age ~ male + intervention, data=bp_dataset, FUN=mean)
##   male intervention      age
## 1    0      Control 53.84615
## 2    1      Control 49.33333
## 3    0       Drug A 56.63636
## 4    1       Drug A 47.73913
## 5    0       Drug B 46.07692
## 6    1       Drug B 45.72000


We can also calculate the median, standard deviation, variance, minimum, maximum, range and sum.
Note The commands ‘sd’ and ‘var’ calculate the sample sd and variance, not the population sd and variance.

sd(age)
## [1] 12.31116
median(age)
## [1] 47
var(age)
## [1] 151.5647
min(age)
## [1] 26
max(age)
## [1] 81
range(age)
## [1] 26 81
sum(age)
## [1] 4903


We can also calculate percentiles. Using the ‘quantile’ command we can set the quantiles that we wish to find. Note that the 0.5 quantile is the median.

quantile(age, probs = c(.25, .5, .75))
##   25%   50%   75% 
## 40.00 47.00 56.25

To get the inter-quartile range (75th percentile minus 25th percentile):

IQR(age)
## [1] 16.25

We can create a frequency table for categorical variables using the ‘table’ command.

table(male)

##  0  1

If we also wish to calculate proportions or percentages, we can use the ‘prop.table’ command. We first need to create the table and then pass to ‘prop.table’.

table.male<-table(male)

prop.table(table.male)

table(male[age>50])

5.2 Normal distribution

We can use R to get the cumulative density function (cdf) of a given normal distribution, based on the mean and sd. For example, to find the proportion of people with blood pressure less than 80, assuming mean BP=112 and SD is 15, we can use the ‘pnorm’ command.

pnorm(80, mean=112, sd=15)
## [1] 0.0164487

To find the proportion of people with BP above 125 we can use the code below.
Note The argument lower.tail=FALSE tells the pnorm function to return the value to the right of the given value.

pnorm(125, mean=112, sd=15, lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 0.1930623

The same result can be obtained by using the command ‘1-pnorm’.

1-pnorm(125, mean=112, sd=15)
## [1] 0.1930623

The command ‘qnorm’ gives the inverse of the cdf (i.e. Z-score for the associated quantile). For example, for quantiles of the standard normal distribution (mean=0, sd=1) Z-score for 95th quantile:

qnorm(0.95, mean=0, sd=1)
## [1] 1.644854

Z-score for 10th quantile:

qnorm(0.1, mean=0, sd=1)
## [1] -1.281552

5.3 Confidence intervals

You will need to install package ‘Rmisc’ for this section.

2-sided confidence interval
We will start by calculating a 2-sided 95% confidence interval for a mean, using the age variable. The command ‘CI’ is used. The 95% CI is the most common certainty level used: this is indicated by the ‘ci’ argument.

CI(age, ci=0.95)
##   upper    mean   lower 
## 51.4728 49.0300 46.5872

For a 2-sided 99% CI:

CI(age, ci=0.99)
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 52.26341 49.03000 45.79659

One-sided CI
For a one-sided CI, calculate the two-sided CI that corresponds to the required upper or lower bound. For example, for a lower 80% CI, calculate the 60% CI and take upper bound.

CI(age, ci=0.60)
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 50.07062 49.03000 47.98938


5.3.0.1 Task 8

Calculate the 2-sided 80% and 90% CI for bp_baseline.

CI(bp_baseline, ci=0.80)
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 185.5881 182.4000 179.2119
CI(bp_baseline, ci=0.90)
##   upper    mean   lower 
## 186.503 182.400 178.297

Calculate the 1-sided lower 97.5th% CI for bp_baseline.

CI(bp_baseline, ci=0.95)
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 187.3032 182.4000 177.4968

CI for subgroups
For example, to calculate the 90% CI for age by sex:

group.CI(age~male,data=bp_dataset, ci=0.90)
##   male age.upper age.mean age.lower
## 1    0  55.76390 51.94595  48.12799
## 2    1  49.66096 47.31746  44.97396


5.3.0.2 Task 9

Calculate the 95% CI for baseline BP for each intervention group.

group.CI(bp_baseline~intervention ,data=bp_dataset, ci=0.95)
##   intervention bp_baseline.upper bp_baseline.mean bp_baseline.lower
## 1      Control          183.3851         174.6786          165.9721
## 2       Drug A          189.7317         181.2647          172.7977
## 3       Drug B          197.4741         189.1053          180.7365

5.4 Random sampling

5.4.1 Sampling from a dataset

We may sometimes wish to randomly select a subset of participants from a dataset. We can use the ‘sample’ function in R.

To select 5 rows from our dataframe bp_dataset:

bp_dataset[sample(nrow(bp_dataset), 5), ]
##    ptid male age intervention bp_baseline bp_3m bp_6m
## 31   31    1  31       Drug A         186   164   135
## 44   44    1  53       Drug A         213   167   130
## 46   46    1  47       Drug B         177   184   173
## 49   49    1  45       Drug A         164   132   116
## 53   53    1  52       Drug A         187   148   144

Alternatively, we can use the ‘sample_n’ function from the ‘dplyr’ package. Ensure that the ‘dplyr’ package is installed.

install.packages("dplyr")
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/kb/jl1t107j50ngpn4dsk20mq8h0000gn/T//RtmpxLDYc7/downloaded_packages
library(dplyr)

To select 10 rows from our dataframe bp_dataset:

sample_n(bp_dataset, 10)
##    ptid male age intervention bp_baseline bp_3m bp_6m
## 1    87    0  75       Drug A         195   139   119
## 2    59    0  42       Drug B         214   164   179
## 3     2    0  46       Drug B         200   162   177
## 4    32    0  39       Drug B         168   172   167
## 5    38    1  43       Drug B         147   169   159
## 6     4    0  46       Drug A         202   148   128
## 7    70    0  40      Control         153   220   188
## 8     1    1  41       Drug B         218   153   163
## 9    13    1  54       Drug A         177   149   148
## 10   53    1  52       Drug A         187   148   144

We may also wish to generate a random sample of numbers from a specific distribution.


To simulate 5 numbers from a uniform distribution between 0 and 1:

runif(5,0,1)
## [1] 0.67887523 0.36388035 0.98919966 0.07308645 0.56859038

To simulate 10 numbers from a normal distribution with mean =0 and SD =5:

rnorm (10, mean = 0, sd = 5)
##  [1] -0.5226447 -3.4601028  2.0191917 -3.0713233  4.4258995  5.3138768
##  [7]  0.3625148 -0.1828069  1.3567016  7.0279121

To simulate Bernoulli/binomial trials:

rbinom ( observations, trials per observation, probability of success for each trial)

For a single observation of one Bernoulli trial, p(success)=0.2:

rbinom(1, 1, 0.2)
## [1] 0

For five observations of one Bernoulli trial, p(success)=0.7:

rbinom(5, 1, 0.7)
## [1] 1 0 0 0 0

For one observation of a binomial distribution, 10 trials, p(success=0.8):

rbinom(1, 10, 0.8)
## [1] 7

The number of successes (out of a maximum of 10) is returned.

For 5 observations of a binomial distribution, 20 trials, p(success=0.25):

rbinom(5, 20, 0.25)
## [1] 3 4 9 6 7

The number of successes (out of a maximum of 20) for each observation is returned.


5.4.1.1 Task 10

Simulate a series of 5 observations of tossing a coin 20 times per observation. Assume the coin is biased with a probability of tossing a head=0.6 (a ‘success’ is tossing a head).

rbinom(5, 10, 0.6)
## [1] 7 6 6 3 8

5.5 Normality testing

Prior to performing statistical tests that are based on the assumption of a normally distributed variable, we wish to test the assumption of normality. One way to do this is with a histogram.
Basic syntax: hist (v, main, xlab, xlim, ylim, breaks,col,border)
v is the variable that is being plotted.

As an example, we can create a histogram of age.

hist(age)


We can add a title (main), x-axis label (xlab), set limitations to the axes (xlim, ylim), set the number of bins (breaks), and colours for the columns and borders.

hist(age, main="Age at baseline", 
     xlab="Age (years)",
     xlim=c(25,90), 
     ylim=c(0,20), 
     breaks=15,
     col="blue",
     border="red")


We can also get details about the histogram, e.g. bin boundaries, number of observations in each bin.

hage<-hist(age, main="Age at baseline", 
     xlab="Age (years)",
     xlim=c(25,90), 
     ylim=c(0,20), 
     breaks=15,
     col="green",
     border="black")

hage
## $breaks
##  [1] 25 30 35 40 45 50 55 60 65 70 75 80 85
## 
## $counts
##  [1]  3  9 16 18 18 10  7  6  7  4  1  1
## 
## $density
##  [1] 0.006 0.018 0.032 0.036 0.036 0.020 0.014 0.012 0.014 0.008 0.002 0.002
## 
## $mids
##  [1] 27.5 32.5 37.5 42.5 47.5 52.5 57.5 62.5 67.5 72.5 77.5 82.5
## 
## $xname
## [1] "age"
## 
## $equidist
## [1] TRUE
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "histogram"

To get just the bin boundaries:

hage$breaks
##  [1] 25 30 35 40 45 50 55 60 65 70 75 80 85

We can also add a normal curve.

hist(age, main="Age at baseline", 
     xlab="Age (years)",
     xlim=c(25,90), 
     ylim=c(0,20), 
     breaks=15,
     col="blue",
     border="red")
curve (dnorm(x, mean=mean(age), sd=sd(age)), add=TRUE, col="black")

We can also add a line to show the density of age.

hist(age, main="Age at baseline", 
     xlab="Age (years)",
     xlim=c(25,90), 
     ylim=c(0,20), 
     breaks=15,
     col="yellow",
     border="blue")
lines(density(age), add=TRUE)
## Warning in plot.xy(xy.coords(x, y), type = type, ...): "add" is not a graphical
## parameter

We can also create overlapping histograms for subgroups using ‘ggplot’. You need to make sure package ‘ggplot2’ is installed.

install.packages("ggplot2")
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/kb/jl1t107j50ngpn4dsk20mq8h0000gn/T//RtmpxLDYc7/downloaded_packages
library(ggplot2)

Website for colours in R
https://r-charts.com/colors/

To change fill and outline color manually:

ggplot(bp_dataset, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(color = intervention, fill = intervention), 
                 position = "identity", bins = 15, alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#8EE5EE")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#8EE5EE"))

We can also create a histogram by sex if we create a factor variable using the variable male, which is coded as 0 and 1.

male_factor<-factor(male)

class(male_factor)
## [1] "factor"
levels(male_factor)
## [1] "0" "1"
ggplot(bp_dataset, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(color = male_factor, fill = male_factor), 
                 position = "identity", bins = 15, alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800"))

We can also create separate histograms for different subgroups. It is necessary to use the male variable coded as 0 and 1 for this command.

ggplot(bp_dataset, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "white", colour = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~male)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can also use a boxplot.

boxplot(age)

We can create separate boxplots by age or intervention.

boxplot(age ~ male_factor)

boxplot(age ~ intervention)

For different colours use:

boxplot(age ~ intervention,
        col = c("#FFE0B2", "#FFA726", "#F57C00"))


We can also perform a Shapiro-Wilk test for normality.

shapiro.test(age)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  age
## W = 0.959, p-value = 0.003415

5.6 Correlation

Before we perform a correlation test we can create a scatterplot to check the relationship between variables. For example, to check the relationship between age and bp_baseline:

plot(age, bp_baseline)

For a Pearson correlation, remember that variables should be distributed normally and with a linear relationship. The Pearson correlation is the default method for the ‘cor.test’ command. We can use ‘cor.test’ to find the Pearson correlation between age and bp_baseline

cor.test(age, bp_baseline)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  age and bp_baseline
## t = 0.11268, df = 98, p-value = 0.9105
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1854507  0.2073366
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## 0.01138201

For a Spearman correlation, we use `cor.test’ but change the ‘method’ argument:

cor.test(age, bp_baseline, method="spearman")
## Warning in cor.test.default(age, bp_baseline, method = "spearman"): Cannot
## compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  age and bp_baseline
## S = 165406, p-value = 0.9412
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##         rho 
## 0.007464794

Calculate the Pearson and Spearman correlation between bp_baseline and bp_3m.

5.7 T-test

5.7.0.1 One-sample t-test

There are several types of t-test. We will start with the simplest: a one-sample 2-sided t-test to test the null hypothesis that the true mean is equal to a pre-specified value. For example, we can use a t-test to test if true mean age=50.

t.test(age, mu=50)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = -0.7879, df = 99, p-value = 0.4326
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 50
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  46.5872 51.4728
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     49.03

t-test to test if true mean age=53:

t.test(age, mu=53)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = -3.2247, df = 99, p-value = 0.001709
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 53
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  46.5872 51.4728
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     49.03

We can vary the width of the confidence interval provided as part of the t-test output - the default is 95% CI.

t.test(age, mu=50, conf.level=0.90)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = -0.7879, df = 99, p-value = 0.4326
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 50
## 90 percent confidence interval:
##  46.98587 51.07413
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     49.03

We can also specify the dataset and a subset of the data if needed. For example, in females only:

female_only<-subset(bp_dataset, male==0)
head(female_only)
##    ptid male age intervention bp_baseline bp_3m bp_6m
## 2     2    0  46       Drug B         200   162   177
## 3     3    0  37       Drug A         198   122   166
## 4     4    0  46       Drug A         202   148   128
## 7     7    0  65      Control         166   140   152
## 8     8    0  69       Drug A         201   141   113
## 11   11    0  53       Drug A         186   107   122
detach(bp_dataset)
attach(female_only)
t.test(age, mu=50)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = 0.8605, df = 36, p-value = 0.3952
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 50
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  47.35957 56.53232
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  51.94595
attach(bp_dataset)
## The following objects are masked from female_only:
## 
##     age, bp_3m, bp_6m, bp_baseline, intervention, male, ptid

We can also specify a 1-sided t-test looking for whether the true mean of the variable is greater than or less than the specified value. To test whether true mean age is less than 50:

t.test(age, mu=50, alternative="less")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = -0.7879, df = 99, p-value = 0.2163
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is less than 50
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 51.07413
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     49.03

To test whether true mean age is greater than 45:

t.test(age, mu=45, alternative="greater")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age
## t = 3.2735, df = 99, p-value = 0.000732
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 45
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  46.98587      Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     49.03


5.7.1 Two-sample unpaired t-test

In this example, we wish compare males and females for age, or in other words we wish to know whether the true mean age is equal for males and females.

age is the response variable (also called outcome variable or dependent variable); we are comparing mean age in Group 1 (male) with mean age in Group 0 (female), i.e. mean difference= Group 1 mean - Group 0 mean.

Note This version of the t-test assumes unequal variance.

t.test(age~male)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age by male
## t = 1.739, df = 63.594, p-value = 0.08687
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.6891826  9.9461538
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        51.94595        47.31746

We can also use a factor variable to indicate the two groups (i.e. as opposed to an integer variable with groups coded as numbers).

t.test(age~male_factor)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age by male_factor
## t = 1.739, df = 63.594, p-value = 0.08687
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.6891826  9.9461538
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        51.94595        47.31746

We can test for equal variance by using an F test. To compare the variance of age by male:

var.test(age ~ male)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  age by male
## F = 1.5248, num df = 36, denom df = 62, p-value = 0.1431
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8663612 2.8110952
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           1.524841

An alternative is Bartlett’s test:

bartlett.test(age ~ male)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  age by male
## Bartlett's K-squared = 2.0664, df = 1, p-value = 0.1506

If we wish to repeat the t-test using the assumption of equal variance:

t.test(age~male, var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age by male
## t = 1.8368, df = 98, p-value = 0.06927
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3721683  9.6291395
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        51.94595        47.31746

5.7.2 Paired t-test: comparing pairs of matched values

A paired t-test is used to compare two variables that are matched or paired in some way, for examples, measurements made on the same person at two different times. For example, we may wish to perform a paired- t-test to test whether the true mean difference between BP at baseline (bp_baseline) and BP at 3 months (bp_3m), measured in the same person, is equal to 0.

t.test(bp_3m,bp_baseline,paired=TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  bp_3m and bp_baseline
## t = -4.5608, df = 99, p-value = 1.462e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -23.707166  -9.332834
## sample estimates:
## mean difference 
##          -16.52

Note that the results are different if we do not take into account the paired nature of the variables.

t.test(bp_3m,bp_baseline,paired=FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  bp_3m and bp_baseline
## t = -4.8468, df = 197.48, p-value = 2.534e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -23.241544  -9.798456
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##    165.88    182.40

5.8 ANOVA

We perform a one-way ANOVA (ANalysis Of VAriance test) to compare means across three or more groups. For example, to compare mean BP at 3 months across Drug A, Drug B, Control:

oneway.drug <- aov(bp_3m ~ intervention)

summary(oneway.drug)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## intervention  2  12718    6359   14.74 2.57e-06 ***
## Residuals    97  41840     431                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
